Biochemical testing is one of the tests for insect susceptibility (resistance or tolerance) to insecticides, in addition to the WHO standard test (susceptibility test) using impregnated paper or paper dyed with insecticides. Biochemical testing is a techn
ique to detect mosquito resistance to essential insecticides based on the quant
ification of enzymes responsible for the resistance process. The advantage of biochemical testing is that information on susceptibility status is obtained more quickly and can show the mechanism of susceptibility reduction (resistance and tolerance) measu
red in individual insects. Measurement of susceptibility status is based on the activity of non-specific esterase enzymes illustrated through the AV value on the Elisa Reader (}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f44\insrsid12403167\charrsid6897024 5}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f44\insrsid6956586\charrsid6897024 ).}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f44\insrsid11606594\charrsid6897024  
\par Pyrethroids are synthetic insecticides from peritin derivatives derived from pyrethrum plants (Tanacetum cinerariaefolium). In general, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f44\insrsid5203216\charrsid6897024 pyrethroid-class}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f44\insrsid11606594\charrsid6897024  insecticides will cause neurotoxic effects on insects (}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f44\insrsid10249045\charrsid6897024 6}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f44\insrsid11606594\charrsid6897024 
). The mechanism of pyrethroids works on the insect nervous system in the form of axon toxins that bind to the Voltage-Gate Sodium Channel (VGSC) which makes the ion channel always open so that the depolarization phase occurs continuously and makes the in
sect become paralyzed and then fall (knock-down) and die (}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f44\insrsid10249045\charrsid6897024 7).}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f44\insrsid11606594\charrsid6897024 
 Mosquitoes with insecticide resistance will find an increase i
n cytochrome P450 (CYP) enzymes, and carboxylesterases (COEs). These enzymes will cause knockdown resistance (kdr) in mosquitoes. The mechanism occurs when mosquitoes are exposed to pyrethroid insecticides. The pyrethroid will cause continuous depolarizat
ion of the VGSC of the mosquito axon which will keep the ion channel open and cause the knock-down effect. In mosquitoes that have experienced resistance, pyrethroid insecticides attached to ion channels will undergo changes to 3-phenoxybenzyl alcohol (PB
Alc) which is not toxic to ion channels so that the ion channels will be closed again so that the depolarization phase becomes normal again and mosquitoes will experience knockdown resistance (kdr) (}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f44\insrsid10249045\charrsid6897024 8).}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f44\insrsid11606594\charrsid6897024  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f44\insrsid10249045\charrsid6897024 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f44\insrsid11606594\charrsid6897024 Another resistance mechanism is the detoxification of pyrethroid insecticides by the esterase enzyme found in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f44\insrsid11606594\charrsid6897024 
Aedes spp.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f44\insrsid11606594\charrsid6897024  The esterase enzyme hydrolyzes the ester bonds in pyrethroid compounds into non-toxic alcohols and acids (}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f44\insrsid10249045\charrsid6897024 9}
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f44\insrsid11606594\charrsid6897024 ). }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f44\insrsid10249045\charrsid6897024 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \f44\insrsid11606594\charrsid6897024 Many studies have shown that increased levels of detoxification enzymes such a
